==Portuguese==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|pt|roa-opt|amigo}}, from {{inh|pt|la|amīcus||friend; friendly}}, from {{m|la|amō||I love}} + {{m|la|-icus}}. Compare Catalan {{m|ca|amic}}, French {{m|fr|ami}}, Italian {{m|it|amico}}, Romanian {{m|ro|amic}} and Spanish {{m|es|amigo}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|PT}} {{IPA|/ɐˈmiɣu/|lang=pt}}
* {{a|BR}} {{IPA|/ɐˈmiɡu/|/aˈmiɡu/|lang=pt}}
* {{a|South Brazil}} {{IPA|/aˈmiɡo/|lang=pt}}

===Noun===
{{pt-noun|m|s|f=amiga}}

# {{l|en|friend}} {{gloss|person whose company one enjoys}}
#: {{ux|pt|João e Maria são meus '''amigos'''.|t=John and Mary are my '''friends'''.}}
# {{l|en|friend}} {{gloss|an associate or thing which provides assistance}}
#: {{ux|pt|Sou '''amigo''' da natureza.|t=I’m a '''friend''' of nature.}}
#: {{ux|pt|Perseverança é a melhor '''amiga''' do conhecimento.|t=Perseverance is knowledge’s best '''friend'''.}}
# a {{l|en|state}} with good {{l|en|relation|relations}} with another state
#: {{ux|pt|O Canadá é '''amigo''' dos Estados Unidos.|t=Canada is the United States’ '''friend'''.}}
# {{lb|pt|Brazil|colloquial|used in the vocative}} {{non-gloss definition|A term of [[address#Noun|address]] for someone}}

====Quotations====
{{seeCites}}

====Synonyms====
